"""
mkt-context — 1 Kings 8–9
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-8-9.py

Ch8: Temple dedication — ark procession, glory cloud, Solomon's prayer (7 scenarios), feast
Ch9: YHWH's second appearance (conditional covenant); administrative records; Ezion-geber fleet
Key context: Deuteronomic šēm theology, seven-petition structure, exile foreseen in dedicatory prayer,
             Gezer archaeology, Ezion-geber excavations, ANE temple dedication parallels
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS1 = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Solomon summoned all the elders of Israel, all the heads of the tribes, and the leaders of the ancestral houses to Jerusalem to bring up the ark from the City of David (Ophel, south of the temple mount). The assembly of the entire national leadership mirrors the covenant assembly at Sinai and at Shechem under Joshua; temple dedication was the most significant corporate act since the nation's founding. Ancient Near Eastern temple dedications similarly required the royal summoning of the entire political and religious leadership of the realm.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The dedication took place in the seventh month — the month of Ethanim (the old Canaanite name; later called Tishri, September-October). This was the month of the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot, Lev 23:33-43), the pilgrimage feast celebrating YHWH's dwelling with Israel in the wilderness. The timing is theologically deliberate: the permanent temple is dedicated at the feast commemorating the temporary tabernacle — the transition from portable tent-sanctuary to permanent stone house occurs at the feast of tents.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The priests carried the ark — correcting the 2 Sam 6 episode where the ark was transported on a cart by non-Levites (resulting in Uzzah's death). Numbers 4:15 specified that the Kohathites were to carry the holy objects including the ark on their shoulders; 1 Chr 15:15 confirms David eventually followed the Levitical protocol. The formal transfer to the permanent temple follows the prescribed procedure.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ark of YHWH was brought up along with the tent of meeting and all the sacred vessels. The tent of meeting (the Tabernacle) had been at Gibeon (2 Chr 1:3) while the ark had been in Jerusalem in a tent David pitched (2 Sam 6:17). The temple dedication reunites the two — the permanent structure that housed YHWH's name at Gibeon and the ark that represented YHWH's presence at Jerusalem are now consolidated in Solomon's temple.</p>",
    "5": "<p>King Solomon and the whole assembly of Israel stood before the ark, sacrificing sheep and oxen 'too numerous to count or record.' The language of incountable sacrifice matches ancient Near Eastern royal dedication inscriptions: Babylonian temple dedication texts describe similar hyperbolic sacrifice counts. The scale signals that this is the supreme national sacrifice, the most significant communal act since the Exodus passover.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The priests brought the ark to the Most Holy Place (qōdeš haqqŏdāšîm, Holy of Holies) — the innermost chamber, a perfect cube 20 cubits on each side (approximately 30 feet, 1 Kgs 6:20). The ark was positioned under the wings of the giant cherubim carved from olive wood overlaid with gold (6:23-28), which stood 10 cubits (15 feet) high with combined wingspan of 20 cubits spanning the entire Holy of Holies. The ark now occupied the physical center of the most holy space in the ancient world.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Two layers of cherub-imagery were now present: (1) the smaller cherubim on the ark's atonement cover (Exod 25:18-22), beaten gold figures facing each other with downward-facing wings; and (2) the massive standing cherubim of the Holy of Holies whose wings met in the center over the ark. Together they formed the divine throne room: YHWH was enthroned between/above the cherubim (1 Sam 4:4; Ps 80:1; Isa 37:16) — the entire innermost chamber was the seat of the divine presence.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The poles were extended so that their tips were visible from the Holy Place at the veil-entrance to the Holy of Holies, but not from outside. Exod 25:15 commanded that the carrying poles remain in the rings permanently: 'The poles shall remain in the rings of the ark; they shall not be removed.' This detail authenticates the ark's identity and honors the original Mosaic instruction even in the permanent temple context.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The ark contained only the two stone tablets that Moses had placed there at Horeb. The Exodus description included a golden jar of manna (Exod 16:33-34) and Aaron's budding staff (Num 17:10); Heb 9:4 understands these as inside the ark. The 1 Kgs 8:9 statement that only the tablets were present has been explained as the other items being lost during the Philistine capture (1 Sam 4-5). The tablets' primacy is theological: the covenant document is the heart of the ark's meaning.</p>",
    "10": "<p>When the priests came out of the Holy Place, a cloud filled the house of YHWH — the glory cloud (ʿānān kāḇôḏ). This directly parallels Exod 40:34-35: 'Then the cloud covered the tent of meeting, and the glory of YHWH filled the tabernacle.' The identical phenomenon at the temple's inauguration establishes continuity between the Tabernacle and the Temple: the same divine presence that filled the portable sanctuary now fills the permanent one. Ezekiel will describe this same glory's departure before the Babylonian destruction (Ezek 10) and its return in the new covenant era (Ezek 43).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The priests could not stand to minister because the glory of YHWH had filled the house — the overwhelming divine presence incapacitates human service. The same occurs when Isaiah sees YHWH in the temple (Isa 6:4) and when Ezekiel sees the glory of YHWH (Ezek 1:28). In Revelation, the temple fills with smoke from YHWH's glory so that no one could enter until the seven plagues were completed (Rev 15:8). YHWH's immediate presence is incompatible with normal human religious activity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH declared that he would dwell in thick darkness (ʿărāpel). The ʿărāpel (deep darkness, thick cloud) is the Sinai theophanic medium: 'Moses drew near to the thick darkness where God was' (Exod 20:21); at Horeb the mountain was burning with 'darkness and cloud and thick darkness' (Deut 4:11; 5:22). YHWH's dwelling in thick darkness is the paradox of divine transcendence: the God of light dwells in impenetrable obscurity, visible to no human eye, yet present between the cherubim.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'I have truly built you an exalted house (bêṯ zəḇul) — a permanent dwelling place.' The phrase bêṯ zəḇul is unusual; zāḇul appears in Ps 49:14 and Hab 3:11 for lofty height. The contrast with YHWH's declaration of 'thick darkness' (v12) is subtly ironic: Solomon calls the house 'exalted'; YHWH's dwelling is 'darkness.' The tension between the king's architectural pride and divine transcendence will be addressed in v27.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The king turned and blessed the whole assembly of Israel while they were standing — the posture of the people (standing) before the king's blessing is significant. Solomon functions here in a quasi-priestly capacity, pronouncing blessing over the covenant people at the temple's founding, mirroring the Aaronic blessing of Num 6:22-27.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Blessed be YHWH, the God of Israel, who spoke with his own mouth to my father David and has fulfilled with his own hand what he promised.' The fulfillment formula (mouth → hand → fulfillment) traces the trajectory from divine word through divine action to historical reality. Solomon's opening historical retrospective grounds the dedication in covenant history, not merely architectural achievement.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'From the day I brought my people Israel out of Egypt, I chose no city from any tribe of Israel in which to build a house for my name to dwell.' The negative statement is striking: Deut 12:5-11 promised YHWH would choose a place, but no specific city had been designated until now. The period from the Exodus to Solomon — roughly 480 years (1 Kgs 6:1) — was a period of anticipation rather than fulfillment. YHWH's non-selection was not indifference but timing.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David's desire to build a house for YHWH's name is recalled — the account from 2 Sam 7:1-3 (David's conversation with Nathan before the night oracle). The desire itself is honored: 'you did well to have it in your heart to build a house for my name.' In ANE theology, the thought behind a gift had moral weight equivalent to the act; YHWH accepts David's unrealized intention.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'You did well to have it in your heart' — divine approval of unrealized intention. This principle extends to all who desire to serve YHWH when circumstances prevent them: the desire is credited. The corollary appears in David's deathbed charge to Solomon (1 Kgs 2:1-4) and in NT teaching about the will oriented toward obedience (John 7:17).</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Your own son who shall be born from your body shall build the house for my name.' The dynastic specification — 'from your body' — is the 2 Sam 7:12 oracle's language. Solomon anchors his building project in the specific prophetic word delivered to David: the temple is the fulfillment of a divine promise, not merely a human religious initiative.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The fulfillment statement is triple: (1) succession to David's throne; (2) building the temple; both as YHWH promised. Solomon's speech is itself a fulfillment liturgy — the act of speaking the fulfillment before the covenant assembly is part of the ceremony of completion.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'I have provided a place for the ark — the ark that holds the covenant of YHWH which he made with our fathers when he brought them out of Egypt.' The ark is explicitly identified with the covenant document. The temple is fundamentally the housing for the covenant — the relational document between YHWH and Israel. Architecture serves theology: the building exists to shelter the covenant, not the covenant to legitimate the building.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Solomon stood before the altar and spread his hands toward heaven — the standard ANE posture of petition and praise. The bronze platform (bikkîyōr, 2 Chr 6:13) measured 5 cubits square and 3 cubits high, elevating Solomon before the entire assembly. The posture of raising hands toward heaven (the divine dwelling) recurs throughout the Psalms (Ps 28:2; 63:4; 134:2).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'YHWH, God of Israel, there is no God like you in heaven above or on earth below' — the incomparability formula (mi-kāmoḵā, who is like you) from the Song of Moses (Exod 15:11). The prayer opens with an assertion of YHWH's absolute uniqueness, which grounds all subsequent petitions: if YHWH is incomparable, his covenant faithfulness is unparalleled, and his ability to act from heaven in every human need is total. The Deuteronomic formula 'you who keep covenant and steadfast love' defines YHWH's character as fundamentally covenantal.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'You kept the promise you made to your servant David — what you spoke with your mouth you have fulfilled with your hand.' The Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7) is the specific basis of Solomon's confidence that YHWH will also hear and answer the petitions that follow: the covenant fulfilled is the ground for the covenant petitions requested.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Keep for your servant David my father what you promised: You shall never lack a man before me to sit on the throne of Israel, if only your sons watch their ways and walk before me as you have walked.' The conditional Davidic promise: dynastic continuity is assured but depends on obedience. The same tension appears in ch9:4-9 — unconditional grace (dynasty promised) and conditional responsibility (obedience required for its maintenance).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Now therefore, O God of Israel, let the word you spoke to your servant David my father be fulfilled.' The petition for fulfillment of an existing promise is a distinct category of prayer in the OT: appealing to YHWH to act in accordance with his own word. Nehemiah (Neh 1:8-9) and Hezekiah (2 Kgs 19:34-35) use the same logic — the prayer claims the promise before the assembled covenant people.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'But will God truly dwell on the earth? Even the highest heavens cannot contain you — how much less this house I have built!' This is the theological climax of the entire dedication. The Deuteronomic theology of the divine name (šēm) dwelling in the sanctuary guards against confusing architectural location with divine presence: YHWH is not contained by the temple; the temple is where YHWH makes his name available for access. Acts 7:48-50 (Stephen's speech) and Acts 17:24 (Paul at Athens) cite this principle directly. The prayer itself witnesses against a simplistic temple theology even as the temple is being dedicated.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Yet give attention to your servant's prayer and plea — listen to the cry and the prayer your servant is praying before you today.' The prayer pivots from transcendence (v27) to accessibility: the God who transcends the cosmos nevertheless attends to human prayer. This is the paradox at the heart of Solomon's prayer: the inconceivable vastness of YHWH and the intimacy of human petition. The same paradox drives the entire prayer corpus of the Psalms.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'That your eyes may be open toward this house night and day — the place where you have said your name will dwell (šimḵā šām).' The 'name theology' (Deuteronomy's šēm formula: the place YHWH will choose to make his name dwell — Deut 12:5, 11, 21; 14:23-24; 16:2; 26:2) is the theological framework for the temple's role: not YHWH's body but YHWH's name is present. The name represents YHWH's character, authority, and accessibility — the temple is where his self-disclosure is concentrated and human approach is authorized.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Hear in heaven your dwelling place (bimĕqôm šiḇtəḵā haššāmayim).' Prayer is directed toward Jerusalem but YHWH hears from heaven. This dual spatial logic creates the theological coherence: the temple is not where YHWH lives but where his name is — YHWH himself is in heaven; his name-presence makes the temple the authorized access point for prayer toward that heaven-dwelling God.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The first petition scenario: individual disputes requiring an oath before the altar. Leviticus 5:1-6 and Exod 22:7-13 specified oath-procedures for disputed property and crimes. The temple altar as the sacred oath-location makes perjury a direct offense against YHWH, ensuring divine justice even when human courts fail or are corrupted (as in ch21, Naboth's trial).</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Hear in heaven and act. Judge your servants: condemn the guilty by bringing his deed on his own head, and vindicate the righteous by rewarding him according to his righteousness.' The judicial petition identifies YHWH as the ultimate court of appeal. The temple's oath-function makes it a place where the powerless can seek justice that wealth cannot corrupt.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The second petition scenario: military defeat caused by Israel's sin. The covenant curse framework (Lev 26:17; Deut 28:25) understood military defeat as divine discipline for covenant violation. The prescribed response — turning back, confessing YHWH's name, and praying toward the temple — is the covenant restoration protocol. Military defeat is theologically interpretable: it is not merely political but a message from YHWH requiring a theological response.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Hear in heaven and forgive the sin of your people Israel and bring them back to the land you gave to their fathers.' The land-exile-restoration pattern is already embedded in the temple dedication prayer: even at the moment of the temple's inauguration, the prayer anticipates the possibility of exile and the mechanism for restoration (repentance + prayer toward the temple). This forward-looking structure reflects the Deuteronomic framework: Deut 30:1-10 predicted exile and restoration long before it occurred.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The third petition scenario: drought caused by sin. The drought-sin connection appears throughout the OT (1 Kgs 17-18 is the most dramatic example; Amos 4:7-8; Hag 1:10-11). The Baal cult competed with YHWH worship partly because Baal was the storm/rain deity; Elijah's drought (ch17-18) directly addresses this competition. The prescription applies covenant theology to ecological crisis.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Teach them the right way to walk and send rain on the land you gave to your people as an inheritance.' The connection between right living and precipitation is covenant theology: the land's productivity is connected to the people's covenant faithfulness (Lev 26:4; Deut 11:14-17). The specific request (rain) is contingent on moral instruction (teach them the right way), linking ecological restoration to relational restoration.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The fourth petition scenario: compound crisis — famine, pestilence, blight, mildew, locusts, grasshoppers, or siege. The list matches the covenant curse catalog of Deut 28:22-24, 38-42. Solomon's prayer essentially asks YHWH to hear when the covenant curses are in effect and the people cry out from within them — a standing provision for the entire range of possible national catastrophes.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Whatever prayer or plea is made by any person or by all your people Israel — each knowing the affliction of his own heart (maḵʾōḇ ləḇāḇô) and spreading out his hands toward this house.' The phrase 'affliction of his own heart' is one of the most theologically precise in the entire prayer: individual, internalized awareness of one's own spiritual condition is the precondition for effective prayer.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'Give to each person according to his ways, whose heart you know — for you alone know the hearts of all people (ʾattāh yāḏaʿtā ləḇaddeḵā ʾet-lēḇāḇ kol-bənê hāʾāḏām).' The divine heart-knowledge is one of the OT's most explicit statements of divine omniscience. Only the one who knows every heart can give to each person according to their ways. Jer 17:10 ('I YHWH search the heart') and Heb 4:13 develop the same theme.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'So that they may fear you all the days they live in the land you gave to our fathers.' The goal of the entire fourth petition is covenant formation: the experience of YHWH hearing prayer produces the fear of YHWH (Prov 1:7; 9:10). Each crisis, heard and answered, becomes a formative event in Israel's knowledge of YHWH.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The fifth petition scenario: prayer by a foreigner (nāḵrî, outsider, non-Israelite) who comes from a distant land because of YHWH's name. This is the most theologically striking of the seven scenarios: a Gentile's prayer at the temple is to be heard. The premise — that foreigners will hear of YHWH's name and come — is the OT basis for Gentile inclusion in the covenant people. The Queen of Sheba (ch10) is the paradigm case.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'For they will hear of your great name and your mighty, outstretched arm.' The 'outstretched arm' is the Exodus formula for YHWH's self-disclosure to Egypt and Israel (Deut 4:34; 5:15; 6:21; 7:19). The prayer anticipates that YHWH's reputation will spread to the nations as it did from the Exodus: the Gentile foreigner coming to pray is drawn by the report of YHWH's historical acts.</p>",
    "43": "<p>'Hear in heaven your dwelling place and grant everything for which the foreigner prays — so that all the peoples of the earth may know your name and fear you, as your people Israel do.' The goal of the foreigner petition is universal knowledge of YHWH: all peoples knowing YHWH's name. This is the Exodus goal extended to the temple era (Exod 9:16: 'so that my name may be proclaimed in all the earth'). The temple is designed to function as a house of prayer for all nations — the text Jesus cites when cleansing the temple (Isa 56:7; Mark 11:17).</p>",
    "44": "<p>The sixth petition scenario: war prayer. When Israel goes out to battle 'by whatever way you send them' — the emphasis on divine commission distinguishes authorized warfare from self-initiated military adventure. The prayer direction (toward the city YHWH has chosen and the house Solomon built) becomes the focal point of military petition.</p>",
    "45": "<p>'Hear their prayer and plea in heaven and uphold their cause (wəʿāśîtā mišpāṭām).' The military petition is framed in legal terminology: uphold their cause/right. YHWH's involvement in warfare is juridical — he is the supreme judge who adjudicates between peoples. The Psalms' battle-prayer tradition (Pss 44, 60, 68, 108) builds on this framework.</p>",
    "46": "<p>'If they sin against you — for there is no one who does not sin (kî ʾên ʾādām ʾăšer lōʾ yēḥĕṭāʾ).' The parenthetical statement of universal sinfulness is the most important theological premise in the prayer: the entire seven-petition structure assumes that the covenant people will sin and need forgiveness. The temple's entire function is predicated on universal human sinfulness. Paul cites this tradition in Rom 3:23 ('all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God').</p>",
    "47": "<p>'Yet if in the land of their captivity they come to their senses and repent, and pray to you in their captors' land, saying: We have sinned, we have acted perversely, we have acted wickedly.' The exile-repentance scenario is the climactic seventh petition. The tripartite confession — sinned (ḥāṭāʾnû), acted perversely (heʿěwînû), acted wickedly (rāšaʿnû) — is the most complete confession formula in the OT, covering intentional, twisted, and blatant sin.</p>",
    "48": "<p>'If they return to you with all their heart and soul in the land of their enemies, and pray toward their own land that you gave to their fathers, the city you have chosen, and the house I have built for your name.' The exile-prayer direction — toward Jerusalem — becomes the practice Daniel adopts while in Babylon (Dan 6:10: 'three times a day he got down on his knees and prayed... his windows were open toward Jerusalem'). Daniel was following the protocol established in this dedicatory prayer centuries earlier.</p>",
    "49": "<p>'Hear their prayer and their plea from heaven, your dwelling place, and uphold their cause.' The seventh petition follows the same structure as the others: pray → YHWH hears from heaven → divine action. The consistency across all seven scenarios establishes the principle's universality: in every circumstance — personal, collective, military, ecological, or exilic — the same pattern applies.</p>",
    "50": "<p>'Forgive your people who have sinned and move their captors to show them compassion (lərāḥămîm).' The request that YHWH move pagan captors to show compassion is a remarkable petition: it asks for YHWH's sovereignty over foreign nations to be exercised in Israel's favor. Isaiah's announcement that Cyrus would be YHWH's shepherd to restore Israel (Isa 44:28; 45:1) is the fulfillment — YHWH moves a Persian king's heart toward Israel's restoration (Ezra 1:1-4).</p>",
    "51": "<p>'For they are your people, your own inheritance (naḥălāṯəḵā), whom you brought out of Egypt, out of that iron-smelting furnace.' The Exodus identity-claim is the final ground of the exile-restoration petition: Israel's identity as YHWH's naḥălāh is rooted in the Exodus, not in subsequent behavior. The 'iron-smelting furnace' (kur habbarzzel) is the Deuteronomic metaphor for Egypt's oppression (Deut 4:20; Jer 11:4) — the people who came through the furnace cannot be abandoned in the furnace of exile.</p>",
    "52": "<p>'May your eyes be open to your servant's plea and to your people Israel's plea, listening to them whenever they call to you.' The closing petition uses the same 'eyes open' language as v29 — forming an inclusio around the seven-petition body. Both personal (Solomon's) and corporate (all Israel's) prayer are within the scope of the temple's intercession function.</p>",
    "53": "<p>'For you separated them from all the peoples of the earth to be your inheritance, as you declared through your servant Moses.' The closing grounding statement invokes the Mosaic election vocabulary: YHWH separated (bādal) Israel from all peoples (Lev 20:26; Deut 7:6). The appeal to Moses in the dedicatory prayer locates the temple firmly within the continuity of the Mosaic covenant, not as a replacement for it — the temple is the spatial expression of the Sinai relationship.</p>",
    "54": "<p>When Solomon had finished the entire prayer and supplication, he rose from before the altar where he had knelt with hands spread out toward heaven. The kneeling posture (2 Chr 6:13 specifies that Solomon knelt on the bronze platform) was less common than standing in Hebrew prayer — kneeling indicated extraordinary petition and humility. The entire prayer, from v22 to v53, represents one extended, structured liturgical act.</p>",
    "55": "<p>He stood and blessed the whole assembly of Israel with a loud voice. The priestly blessing pattern — standing, loud voice, blessing the congregation — mirrors the Aaronic blessing of Num 6:22-27. Solomon's standing (having just been kneeling, v54) marks the transition from petition to proclamation: the king who prayed in humility now speaks with royal authority over the covenant people.</p>",
    "56": "<p>'Blessed be YHWH, who has given rest to his people Israel in keeping with all his promises. Not one word has fallen to the ground of all his good promise that he gave through his servant Moses.' The 'not one word has failed' declaration echoes Josh 21:45 and 23:14 (Joshua's own testimony of complete covenant fulfillment). The completeness of YHWH's promise-keeping is the foundation for continued trust.</p>",
    "57": "<p>'May YHWH our God be with us as he was with our fathers. May he never abandon or forsake us.' The blessing invokes the divine presence promise from Josh 1:5 and Deut 31:6-8 — YHWH's word to Joshua ('I will not leave you or forsake you') repeated at the new era's beginning. The same promise appears in Heb 13:5 as the NT ground for contentment.</p>",
    "58": "<p>'That he may incline our hearts toward him, to walk in all his ways and keep his commandments, statutes, and ordinances.' The petition for inclined hearts anticipates Ezek 36:26-27 ('I will give you a new heart') and Jer 31:33 ('I will put my law within them'). The blessing requests what Solomon himself will fail to maintain (ch11) and what only the new covenant can guarantee.</p>",
    "59": "<p>'May these words of mine with which I have prayed before YHWH remain near to YHWH our God day and night, that he may uphold the cause of his servant and the cause of his people Israel, as each day requires.' The phrase 'as each day requires' (dəḇar-yôm bəyômô, the matter of a day in its day) is the same phrase used for the daily manna provision (Exod 16:4) — daily adequacy applied to daily covenant maintenance.</p>",
    "60": "<p>'So that all the peoples of the earth may know that YHWH is God — there is no other.' The monotheistic declaration echoes Deut 4:35-39. The temple's ultimate purpose is not national religion but universal witness: every act of YHWH on behalf of Israel is a testimony about divine reality to all peoples. The prophets develop this universal dimension (Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-5; Zech 8:20-23).</p>",
    "61": "<p>'May your heart be wholly devoted (šālēm) to YHWH our God, walking in his statutes and keeping his commandments, as today.' The concluding charge to Israel uses the šālēm (complete, whole heart) vocabulary that will be used against Solomon himself in 11:4 ('his heart was not wholly [šālēm] devoted to YHWH'). The king who exhorts perfect heart-devotion will himself fall short of it — revealing the gap between covenant aspiration and human performance that only the new covenant can bridge.</p>",
    "62": "<p>The king and all Israel offered sacrifices before YHWH — the communal sacrifice that concludes the dedication. The transition from Solomon's prayer (vv22-61) to corporate sacrifice marks the return from liturgical word to covenant action: the prayer is sealed by sacrifice. The pattern anticipates the NT pattern of word and table together constituting covenant worship.</p>",
    "63": "<p>Solomon offered as peace/fellowship offerings (šəlāmîm) 22,000 oxen and 120,000 sheep and goats — the largest single sacrifice recorded in the OT. The middle of the court was consecrated as additional altar space (v64) because the main altar could not accommodate the volume. The fellowship offerings (unlike burnt offerings) involved a communal meal: portions returned to the worshippers for a feast, making the entire assembly participants in the sacrificial banquet before YHWH.</p>",
    "64": "<p>The middle of the court was consecrated as additional altar space because the bronze altar (five cubits high, ten cubits wide on each side) could not accommodate the volume of offerings. The consecration of expanded space signals that the occasion exceeded normal temple capacity — this was the maximum covenant feast in Israel's history.</p>",
    "65": "<p>'Solomon held the feast, and all Israel with him — a great assembly from Lebo-hamath to the Brook of Egypt.' The geographic formula defines the full extent of Solomon's kingdom: Lebo-hamath (the northern limit, at the entrance to the Beqa Valley in Lebanon) to the Brook of Egypt (Wadi el-Arish on the Sinai peninsula, the southern limit). The feast lasted fourteen days (seven for the dedication, seven for the Feast of Tabernacles, 2 Chr 7:8-9) — the confluence of the two great celebrations maximized national participation.</p>",
    "66": "<p>On the eighth day Solomon dismissed the people; they blessed the king and went home 'joyful and glad of heart for all the good that YHWH had done for his servant David and for his people Israel.' The dismissal on the eighth day follows the Tabernacles pattern (Lev 23:36: the eighth day as a solemn assembly). The people's joy is specifically for 'all the good YHWH had done' — their gladness is YHWH-directed, not primarily human-achievement centered. The dedication ends with the people's hearts in the right place, a brief moment before the troubles of ch9-11 begin.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>After completing both the temple and the royal palace and all he desired to build, YHWH appeared to Solomon a second time. The second theophany follows the completion of all major construction projects — a period spanning approximately 20 years (7 years for the temple, 1 Kgs 6:38; 13 years for the palace complex, 7:1). The timing is significant: YHWH's response to the prayer of dedication comes after Solomon has finished the entire building program, not immediately following the ceremony.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'YHWH appeared to Solomon a second time, just as he had appeared to him at Gibeon.' The comparison to Gibeon (the first theophany, ch3) frames the second appearance as a formal divine response. At Gibeon, YHWH gave Solomon a gift (wisdom) in response to his request; now YHWH gives a conditional covenant in response to the temple's completion and the dedicatory prayer.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'I have heard your prayer and your plea. I have consecrated this house that you have built by putting my name there forever (wəšamtî šəmî šām ləʿôlām).' YHWH's response directly addresses the šēm theology of Solomon's prayer (8:29): the name is placed there as promised. The consecration formula (hiqaddaštî, I have made holy) establishes the temple's sacred status through divine declaration, not merely human construction. 'My eyes and my heart will be there perpetually' — YHWH's attention and relational investment are committed to this location.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'As for you, if you walk before me as your father David walked — with integrity and uprightness (bəṯom-lēḇāḇ ûḇəyōšer), doing all I have commanded you, keeping my statutes and ordinances.' The conditional structure of the Solomonic covenant is now made explicit. The standard of comparison is David's — not David's sinlessness but David's integrity of orientation and responsiveness to divine correction. The contrast with Solomon's future failure (11:4: 'his heart was not wholly devoted to YHWH') is already implicit.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Then I will establish your royal throne over Israel forever (ləʿôlām), as I promised your father David: You will never lack a man on the throne of Israel.' The unconditional promise (dynasty established forever) and the conditional requirement (walk as David walked) are held in tension. The resolution comes in the Messianic fulfillment — the one descendant of David who perfectly fulfills the condition (Matt 3:17) and embodies the eternal throne.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'But if you or your children turn away from following me and do not keep my commandments and statutes, and go and serve other gods and worship them.' The threat is stated in the second person — Solomon's own defection is anticipated alongside the general dynastic warning. The specific form of the predicted defection — 'serve other gods and worship them' — is precisely what Solomon does in ch11. YHWH warns against the exact sin Solomon will commit.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Then I will cut off Israel from the land I have given them, and I will cast from my sight this house I consecrated for my name.' The exile threat uses the Deuteronomic vocabulary: 'cut off' (hikrattî) and 'cast from my sight' (šillahttî). The same house just consecrated (v3) will be rejected; the same name just placed (v3) will be removed. Ezekiel's vision of YHWH's glory departing from the temple (Ezek 10-11) is the fulfillment of this conditional threat — departure of the divine presence before the Babylonian destruction in 586 BCE.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'This exalted house will become a ruin. Everyone who passes by will be appalled (šāmam) and will hiss (šāraq), saying, Why has YHWH done this to this land and to this house?' The prophetic description of the ruined temple anticipates the actual language used in Lamentations and in Jeremiah's temple sermon (Jer 7:12-14). The passer-by astonishment formula appears in 1 Kgs 9:8, Jer 18:16; 19:8; 49:17; 50:13; Lam 2:15-16 — a recurring literary form for the incomprehensible reversal of divine favor.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The answer will be: Because they abandoned YHWH their God who brought their fathers out of Egypt, and took hold of other gods and worshipped them and served them.' The question-and-answer structure is a catechetical device for transmitting the theological interpretation of historical catastrophe. The answer is the Deuteronomic formula for the exile: abandonment of YHWH + embrace of other gods = divine judgment. This formula is repeated almost verbatim in 2 Kgs 17:7-23 (the interpretation of the northern exile).</p>",
    "10": "<p>After twenty years of building — the temple and the royal palace — Solomon gave Hiram twenty cities in the land of Galilee. The twenty-year timeline (7 years for the temple, 6:38; 13 for the palace, 7:1) is confirmed by this administrative note. The Galilee cities represent Solomon's payment for the enormous supply of cedar, cypress, and gold that Hiram had provided through the entire building period.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Since Hiram king of Tyre had supplied Solomon with whatever cedar, cypress, and gold he needed, King Solomon gave Hiram twenty cities in the land of Galilee. The commercial arrangement that underpinned the temple construction (ch5) is now being settled. Tyre's proximity to the Galilee region made these border cities potentially valuable to Hiram as territorial expansion into formerly Israelite land.</p>",
    "12": "<p>When Hiram came from Tyre to inspect the towns Solomon had given him, they did not please him. The word lōʾ yāšrû bəʿênāyw (they were not right in his eyes) uses the same evaluative formula used for royal assessments throughout Kings ('right/evil in the eyes of YHWH'). Hiram's disappointment may reflect the towns' poor economic value or agricultural productivity compared to his expectation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Hiram called them 'Cabul' (kāḇûl) — a pun possibly meaning 'like nothing' or 'valueless.' 2 Chronicles 8:2 provides a supplementary note that Solomon eventually recovered these cities; the Cabul episode may reflect an initial payment later renegotiated after Hiram expressed dissatisfaction. Archaeological survey of the Galilee region has identified a site called Kabul that may preserve the ancient name.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Hiram had sent the king 120 talents of gold. This is likely the total gold payment accompanying all of Hiram's cedar and material supply — the financial dimension of the commercial arrangement that ran through the entire building program. Combined with the 420 talents from Ophir (v28), Solomon's gold income during this period was enormous.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The account of Solomon's forced labor (mas) records the administrative realities behind the building program: the Millo (the terracing/fill structure of Jerusalem's City of David, the Stepped Stone Structure attested in archaeology), the city wall, Hazor, Megiddo, and Gezer. These three principal fortifications controlled Israel's major north-south travel corridors. Yadin's 1958-1969 excavations at Hazor and Megiddo identified a distinctive 'Solomonic gate' design at both sites (six-chambered gates), confirmed also at Gezer — striking archaeological confirmation of the Kings narrative.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Pharaoh king of Egypt had captured Gezer, burned it, killed the Canaanites living there, and given it as a dowry gift to his daughter — Solomon's wife. The archaeology of Gezer confirms a destruction layer from approximately the 10th century BCE, followed by construction of the characteristic Solomonic gate style. The Pharaoh who gave Gezer as a dowry is unknown but may have been Siamun of the 21st dynasty (ca. 978-959 BCE).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Solomon rebuilt Gezer and Lower Beth-horon. Lower Beth-horon (on the western descent from Jerusalem toward the coastal plain) was a strategically critical site controlling the pass from the Aijalon Valley — the same route Joshua used for the battle of Gibeon (Josh 10:10-11) and where Judas Maccabeus later defeated the Seleucids. Its fortification protected the approach to Jerusalem from the west.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Baalath and Tamar in the wilderness. Baalath was in the territory of Dan (Josh 19:44), possibly near Gezer. Tamar in the Negev is a desert fortification on the route toward Edom and the Red Sea — possibly identified with 'En Hazeva in the Arabah, excavated in the 1990s. These southern fortifications protected the trade routes to Ezion-geber and the Ophir gold source.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Solomon's building program included store cities (ʿārê hammiskenôt), chariot cities (ʿārê hāreḵeḇ), and cavalry cities (ʿārê hāpārāšîm) — a three-tier military infrastructure distributed across the kingdom. The Megiddo excavations (Oriental Institute, Chicago) revealed large stable complexes from this period, and the six-chambered gate design appears at multiple sites.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The non-Israelite peoples remaining in the land — Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites — were the remnant of the pre-Israelite population that Joshua had not fully destroyed (Josh 9; 11:19-20; Judg 1). Their continued presence centuries after the conquest reflects the incomplete nature of the settlement. Solomon now resolves this through administrative absorption: they become the permanent labor force.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Their descendants still in the land — those the Israelites had been unable to destroy completely (lōʾ yāḵəlû bənê-yiśrāʾēl ləhaḥărîmām) — Solomon conscripted as forced laborers.' The ḥērem (complete destruction) that Joshua was supposed to apply was not fully executed; the Canaanite remnant became the foundation of Solomon's labor system. The same failure that produced ongoing religious temptation (Judg 2:3) now produces economic utility — a rationalization that the incomplete obedience was providential.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'But Solomon did not make any Israelites into slaves; they served as soldiers, his officials, commanders, captains, and commanders of his chariots and cavalry.' The distinction between Canaanite slaves and Israelite soldiers/officials reflects the official social hierarchy. However, the forced labor system applied to Israelites (1 Kgs 5:13-14) was already creating social resentment that would fracture the kingdom in ch12 — the Jeroboam-labor narrative (11:28) and the people's complaint to Rehoboam (12:4) reveal the practical gap between the official distinction and daily reality.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Five hundred and fifty chief officers supervised Solomon's workforce. The parallel in 5:16 gives 3,300 supervisors, and 2 Chr 8:10 gives 250 chief officers — different levels of the supervisory hierarchy are being counted in each passage. The sheer number of supervisors required for Solomon's construction projects indicates the enormous scale of the labor mobilization.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Pharaoh's daughter moved from the City of David to her own palace that Solomon had built for her. 2 Chr 8:11 explains: 'No wife of mine shall dwell in the house of David king of Israel, for the places to which the ark of YHWH has come are holy.' The Millo construction following her move may indicate the expansion of the city's northern defensive terracing to include the new residential area.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Three times a year Solomon offered burnt offerings and peace offerings on the altar — at the three annual pilgrimage feasts (Passover, Weeks, Tabernacles — Deut 16:16; Exod 23:14-17). Solomon's observance is presented positively here, before ch11 reveals his apostasy. The formal covenant observance continued even as the internal spiritual condition deteriorated.</p>",
    "26": "<p>King Solomon built a fleet of ships at Ezion-geber, near Eloth on the shore of the Red Sea, in the land of Edom. Ezion-geber is identified with Tell el-Kheleifeh near modern Aqaba (Jordan)/Eilat (Israel), at the northern end of the Gulf of Aqaba. Nelson Glueck's 1938-1940 excavations identified a substantial site there with evidence of industrial activity. The Red Sea fleet gave Solomon access to the trade routes of the Arabian Peninsula and East Africa, explaining the gold-from-Ophir operations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Hiram sent his own servants — experienced sailors who knew the sea (yōḏəʿê hayyām) — to serve alongside Solomon's men. The Phoenicians (Tyrians) were the Mediterranean world's most experienced sailors; the Israelites had no maritime tradition. The joint venture gives Solomon access to Hiram's seafaring expertise while Hiram gains access to the Red Sea trade routes his Mediterranean fleet could not reach — the same partnership that built the temple now extends to oceanic commerce.</p>",
    "28": "<p>They sailed to Ophir and brought back 420 talents of gold to King Solomon. Ophir's location is debated: proposals include southern Arabia (Yemen), East Africa (Somalia/Eritrea/Ethiopia), or India (Gujarat). The 420 talents of gold (about 15 tons) represents an extraordinary commercial return for a single voyage, confirming the Red Sea trade route as one of the ancient world's most lucrative arteries for precious metals.</p>"
  }
}

